</div><div class="solution"><p>
need a diagrammaths needed</p></div></div></div><h2>Equilibrium</h2><p class="">need some equilibrium examples etc from SJC vectors</p><h2>Newton’s First Law</h2><blockquote class="quote" id="eabf252e-c0a9-05b6-b5fe-b350c8647b4b"><p><span style="font-style: normal; line-height: 20px;">If I have seen further than others, it is by standing on the shoulders of giants.</span></p><p><span style="font-size: 14.666666984558105px; font-style: normal; line-height: 20px;">Sir Isaac Newton</span><br></p></blockquote><p class="" style=""><br style=""></p><p class="">Since the days of Aristotle, many people tried to answer questions about forces&nbsp;and motion. Galileo did a lot of work and thinking about forces, but it was&nbsp;Newton who was able to come up with a general understanding of force and&nbsp;motion.</p><dl class="definition"><dt>Newton's First Law</dt><dd><p class="">An object continues in a state of rest or uniform (moving with constant) velocity&nbsp;unless it is acted upon by a net or resultant force.</p></dd></dl><p class="">Something to consider:</p><p class="">An ice skater pushes away from the side of the ice rink and skates across the ice. She will continue to move in a straight line across the ice unless something&nbsp;stops her. Objects are also like that. If we kick a soccer ball across a soccer field,&nbsp;according to Newton’s First Law, the soccer ball should keep on moving forever.&nbsp;However, in real life this does not happen. Is Newton’s Law wrong? No.&nbsp;</p><p class="">Newton’s First Law applies to situations where there aren’t any net forces&nbsp;present. In the case of the ice skater, the friction between the skates and the&nbsp;ice is very little and she will continue moving for quite a distance. In the case of&nbsp;the soccer ball, air resistance (friction between the air and the ball) and friction&nbsp;between the grass and the ball is present and this will slow the ball down.</p><p class="">Newton’s first law answers our question “What is a force?” A force is what causes an object to change its motion. It also tells us that no force is needed for motion,&nbsp;we only need a force to change the motion.</p><p class=""><br></p><p class="">The following facts arise from Newton’s First Law:</p><ul><li>If a body is stationary or traveling at a constant velocity, it has no net&nbsp;or resultant force acting on it. &nbsp;(e.g. A motor car traveling at a constant 120 km.h<sup>-1</sup> in a straight line.)</li></ul><p class=""><strong>Diagram of car needed</strong></p><p class="">We say that an object that has no net or resultant force acting on it is in equilibrium. A body in equilibrium can be at rest or moving with a constant&nbsp;velocity.</p><ul><li>A resultant force causes a change in the state of rest or motion of a&nbsp;body. &nbsp;(i.e. the body accelerates).</li><li class="" style="">No force is required to keep an object moving at constant velocity. (eg&nbsp;the Voyager spacecrafts)<br style=""><figure class="figure" title=""><div class="title"></div><img draggable="false" alt="" class="aloha-image-uploading" data-lrmi-creator="NASA" data-tbook-permissiontext="Image by NASA.License: Choose a license." src="../../../resources/1fd53ccfb27d8fdf11d3ffb0dad4b150519944ef.jpg"/><figcaption></figcaption></figure></li><li>We wear seat belts in cars. This is to protect us when the car is involved in an accident. If a car is travelling at 120 km.h<sup>-1</sup>, the<br style="">passenger in the car is also travelling at 120 km.h<sup>-1</sup>. When the car suddenly stops a force is exerted on the car (making it slow down), but not on the passenger. The passenger will carry on moving&nbsp;forward at 120 km.h<sup>-1</sup> according to Newton I. If they are wearing a seat belt, the seat belt will stop them by exerting a force on them&nbsp;and so prevent them from getting hurt.</li></ul><p class=""><br></p><p class="">Newton’s first law is also known as the law of inertia.</p><p class="">If an object is at rest it has a tendency to stay at rest. If an object is moving, it has&nbsp;a tendency to continue moving with the same velocity.</p><dl class="definition"><dt>Inertia</dt><dd><p class="">Inertia is the property of an object that causes it to resist a change in its state of&nbsp;rest or uniform motion.</p></dd></dl><p>The extent of the inertia is directly proportional to the mass.</p><p><br></p><p>The following demonstrations illustrate the Law of Inertia:</p><ol><li>Coin on paper<br><br>diagram as per SJC notes<br style=""><br style="">In this example the coin resists the change in motion. A coin with the&nbsp;largest mass will show the least amount of horizontal movement.<br style=""><br style=""></li><li style="">A weight hanging from a string
<p>Diagram as per SJC Notes</p><p>Explain why the top string breaks when pulled slowly at X and why the lower string breaks when given a sudden jerk at X.</p></li><li style="">The accelerometer</li></ol>

<p>
Note: This is an instrument that can indicate the direction of the relative acceleration produced by a resultant force. You can download an accelerometer app on your phone or tablet)</p>
